# Function to plot distplot

def plot_dist(col,title):
    """
    col  : column name
    title: title of the plot (string value)
    """
    #import seaborn as sns
    #import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
    plt.figure(figsize=(16,9))
    sns.set() # for style
    sns.distplot(col)
    #plt.xticks([1.0,1.5,2.0,2.5,3.0,3.5,4.0,4.5,5.0])
    plt.title(title,fontdict= {'fontsize': 24, 'fontweight':'bold'})
    #plt.legend()

# Function to plot barplot

def plot_bar(inp_data,x_axis,x_label,y_label,title):
    """
    inp_data : input dataframe
    x_axis   : column on x_axis (string value)
    x_label  : name on x_label (string value)
    y_label  : name on y_label (string value)
    title    : title of the plot (string value)
    """
    try:
        #import seaborn as sns
        #warnings.filterwarnings('ignore')
        #import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
        sns.set_style(style="darkgrid")
        plt.figure(figsize=(16, 9))
        fig = sns.countplot(x=x_axis,data=inp_data,order=inp_data[x_axis].value_counts().index)
        plt.xlabel(x_label,fontdict= {'fontsize': 18,'fontweight':'bold'},labelpad=20)
        plt.ylabel(y_label,fontdict= {'fontsize': 18,'fontweight':'bold'},labelpad=20)
        plt.title(title,fontdict= { 'fontsize': 24, 'fontweight':'bold'},pad=20)
        plt.xticks(fontsize=13,rotation=45)
        plt.yticks(fontsize=13)
        for p in fig.patches:
            fig.annotate('{:.0f}'.format(p.get_height()), (p.get_x()+0.2, p.get_height()+100),fontsize=12)
        plt.show(fig)
    except TypeError:
        pass

# Confusion Matrix

def cnf_matrix(y_test,pred,mod_name):    
    """    
    y_test   : y_test after train/test split
    pred     : model.predict(X_test)
    mod_name : name of model (string value)    
    """ 
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, pred)
    tn, fp, fn, tp = confusion_matrix(y_test, pred).ravel()
    cm = [[tp,fp],[fn,tn]]
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(4,4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt = "d",cbar=False) #cmap='Blues'
    plt.xlabel('Actual Labels',fontdict= {'fontsize': 12},labelpad=20)
    plt.ylabel('Predicted Labels',fontdict= {'fontsize': 12},labelpad=20)
    plt.title(mod_name+' Regression Confusion Matrix',fontdict= { 'fontsize': 18, 'fontweight':'bold'},pad=20)
    ax.xaxis.set_ticklabels(['Fraud', 'Not Fraud'])
    ax.yaxis.set_ticklabels(['Fraud', 'Not Fraud'])

# ROC_AUC curve

def plot_roc(y_test, pred_dict):    
    """    
    y_test    : y_test after train/test split
    pred_dict : dict consiting of key->string name of model,
                value->predicted probabilities               
    """    
    plt.title('ROC-AUC')
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1],'r--')
    plt.xlim([0, 1])
    plt.ylim([0, 1])
    plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
    plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
    for key, pred in pred_dict.items():
        fpr, tpr, threshold = metrics.roc_curve(y_test, pred)
        roc_auc = metrics.auc(fpr, tpr)
        plt.plot(fpr, tpr, label = '%25s AUC = %0.3f' % (key, roc_auc))
    plt.legend(loc = 'lower right')
    plt.show()

# Feature Importance

def plot_feature_importance(importance, names, mod_name):    
    """    
    importance : model.feature_importances_
    names      : X_train.columns
    mod_name   : name of model (string value)    
    """
    feature_importance = np.array(importance)                
    feature_names = np.array(names)  
    data = {'feature_names': feature_names,                  
            'feature_importance': feature_importance}
    fi_df = pd.DataFrame(data)                               
    fi_df.sort_values(by=['feature_importance'], ascending=False, inplace=True)
    fi_df = fi_df[:15]
    plt.figure(figsize=(16, 9))                                                    
    sns.barplot(x=fi_df['feature_importance'],
                y=fi_df['feature_names'])                                         
    plt.title(mod_name + " " + 'Feature Importance (Top 15)',
              weight='bold')                                                       
    plt.xlabel('Feature Importance')
    plt.ylabel('Feature Names')
In [6]:
# PR Curve

def plot_pr_curve(y_test, pred_proba, mod_name):
    """
    y_test     : y_test after train/test split
    pred_proba : predicted probabilities
    mod_name   : name of model (string value)
    
    """
    precision, recall, _ = precision_recall_curve(y_test, pred_proba)
    plt.plot(recall, precision, marker='.', label=mod_name)
    plt.xlabel('Recall')
    plt.ylabel('Precision')
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

# Classification Report

def report_classification(mod_report):
    """
    mod_report : dict consiting of key->string name of model,
                 value-> predicted value 
    """
    for k,v in mod_report.items():
        print('Classification Report for '+k)
        print(classification_report(y_test, v))
        print('--------------------------------------------------------------')

# AUC & PR score

def roc_auc_pr(mod_report):
    """
    mod_report : dict consiting of key->string name of model,
                 value-> predicted probabilities 
    """
    for k,v in mod_report.items():    
        print('ROC-AUC score for '+k+':')
        print(round(roc_auc_score(y_test, v),4))
        print('\n')
        print('PR-AUC score for '+k)
        precision, recall, _ = precision_recall_curve(y_test, v)
        print(round(auc(recall, precision),4))
        print('---------------------------')

Question 3: Data Wrangling - Duplicate Transactions¶

You will notice a number of what look like duplicated transactions in the data set. One type of duplicated transaction is a reversed transaction, where a purchase is followed by a reversal. Another example is a multi-swipe, where a vendor accidentally charges a customer's card multiple times within a short time span.

3.1 Can you programmatically identify reversed and multi-swipe transactions?¶

Reversed Transaction¶

The reversed transactions are mentioned in transactionType column.

In [45]:
print('Number of reversed transaction in the dataset :'+ str(len(df_find_dupe.query('transactionType == "REVERSAL"'))))

Number of reversed transaction in the dataset :20303
  • Assumption

Initially I was assuming that all transactionType = REVERSE would fall under the category of being a "duplicated transaction". Reading a bit more about reverse transactions, i realised it's not exactly same as refund transactions, which i had originally assumed. There's a fundamental difference between both which helped in my hypothesis of labeling when we can label a reversed transaction as duplicate

A refund occurs when a transaction is posted and the funds are already in the merchantâ€™s account. On the other hand, a reversal occurs when the transaction is halfway through the process; that is, it is yet to post.

So, my final understanding is that the duplicate tranasction in our case can be defined as those where transactionType "purchase" is followed by a reversal in a short amount of time since we read just above that reversal occurs when the transaction is halfway through the process

Source: https://getoutofdebthub.com/difference-between-refund-and-reversal-transaction/

Multi-Swipe transactions¶

Multi-swipe transaction will occur when the same account has a consequent transaction of the same amount in a very small period of time. So, a "purchase" will be followed by another "purchase" transaction.

"Short time" Range Calculation¶

There is no specific threshold of how each bank defines the time length for a transaction to be considered duplicate

So one approach I took is to look at the number of transactions in time slots of 30 seconds which an assumption of upper boundary of 15min because mostly a fraudster would do multiple transactions in short amount of time before the owner realises that they have been duped, so there's a short time of window for a fraudster and that is what i wanted to derive at

In [46]:
# Create a copy of original dataframe for analysis
df_short_time = df_find_dupe.copy(deep=True)

# Time difference on seconds between transactions
df_short_time['time_diff_sec'] = (df_short_time.transactionDateTime - df_short_time.transactionDateTime.shift(1)).astype('timedelta64[s]')

# Similar Account
df_short_time['same_account'] = df_short_time.customerId - df_short_time.customerId.shift(1)

# Transactions that happened under 15 min for same customer
df_trans_15 = df_short_time[(df_short_time['time_diff_sec']<=1800) & (df_short_time['time_diff_sec']>0) & (df_short_time['same_account']==0)]

  • Assumption (based on analysis)

We can observe a pattern here. The number of transactions fluctuates a lot in the first 180 seconds after that it becomes very flat. Based on this pattern, I choose 180 seconds as the threshold of "Short Time Range" to derive duplicates

Final logic to calculate duplicate transaction

So, putting all the pieces together. Following are the steps to calculate duplicate transactions-

  1. Group the transactions by Account Number, Merchant Name, Transaction Amount and cardLast4Digits
  2. Sort by transaction date
  3. Compute the time difference between each of the subsequent requests (in seconds)
  4. Flag all the transactions that have a time gap of less than 3 min/180 secs (threshold picked based on analysis)
  5. Pick the transaction with flagged value as True

Note: This logic will automatically label the first transaction to be "normal" and exclude it from the duplicate transaction thus meeting the criteria of the question

In [48]:
# Applying the above mentioned logic
# Creating a flag dupe_trans which means a flag to check if the transaction is duplicate or not

df_find_dupe['dupe_trans'] = (df_find_dupe.sort_values(['transactionDateTime'])
                       .groupby(['customerId', 'transactionAmount','merchantName','cardLast4Digits'], sort=False)['transactionDateTime']
                       .diff()
                       .dt.total_seconds()
                       .lt(181))

df_new["trans_month"] = df_new.transactionDateTime.dt.month                 #transaction month

# Time of the day 
# Divided the day into 4 timings essentially: morning, afternoon, evening, night
df_new["time_of_day"] = pd.cut(df_new.trans_hour, bins=4, labels=['Morning', 'afternoon', 'evening', 'night'])

# Weekday/Weekend flag
df_new["weekday"] = df_new.trans_day_of_week < 5

# Days since last address change 
df_new["since_days_lastAddressChange"] = (df_new.transactionDateTime - df_new.dateOfLastAddressChange).dt.days

# Total amount spent each day
df_new["total_spent_one_day"] = (

    .reset_index("customerId")

    .sort_index()
    .squeeze()
)

    )
    .reset_index("customerId")
    .drop("customerId", axis=1)
    .sort_index()
    .squeeze()
)

# Transactions that happen in separate countries, but minutes apart

df_new["trans_time_shift_down1"] = df_new.groupby("customerId").transactionDateTime.shift(1)
df_new["country_shift_down1"] = df_new.groupby("customerId").acqCountry.shift(1)
ctry_diff = df_new.acqCountry != df_new.country_shift_down1
in_window = (df_new.transactionDateTime - df_new.trans_time_shift_down1) < pd.Timedelta("3 minutes")
df_new["diff_country_three_min"] = (ctry_diff & in_window).fillna(False)

1. Resampling Methods

  • Undersampling
    We create a subset of the original data set by eliminating instances (usually majority class instances).
  • Oversampling
    We create a sub set of the original data set by replicating some instances or creating new instances from existing ones.

  • Hybrid
    Mix of both undersampling & oversampling techniques

    NOTE: Always split the date into test and train sets BEFORE trying sampling techniques!

2. Cross-Validation

  • Using stratified k-fold cross validation would be a good way of approaching this problem,Stratification will ensure that the percentages of each class in our entire data will be the same (or very close to) within each individual fold.

3. Adjusting class weights/ Cost-Sensitive Training

  • In general, classification models weigh each class equally. we can change the weights of classes so that a misclassification of an observation in a minority class outweighs a misclassification of majority class. In Some algo we cab increase the cost of classification mistakes on the minority class, which would be another right way of approching our problem.

4. Threshold-Moving for Imbalanced Classification

3. Interpreting the problem & Trade-offs¶

Trade off

Now lets forsee the outcomes of our model and it's monetary impact
Given that, we will have different costs for different predicted outputs.

1.True Positive (TP): the model predicts its a fraud given it is really a fraud, we cancel the transaction correctly, the bank will have no costs or just administration fees.

2.True Negative (TN): the model predicts the transaction is not fraudulent and it actually isn't, the bank will approve it and no costs occur. ($0)

3.False Positive (FP): the model predicts its a fraud given it actually is not fraud, Bank will need to pay for the customer service fee (and potentially the cost of losing a customer).

4.False Negative (FN): the model predicts its a non-fraudulent transaction given it actually is a fraud, bank approve the order wrongly and need to pay for the chargebacks while losing the amount of the order.(example-dependent)

FP: false positives are very harmful because they prevent customers from using their credit cards, repeated FP for a customer may end in potentailly losing the customer
FN: False negatives are obviously very impactful as it's causing banks loose lot of money.

So we see, the penalty for mislabeling a fraud transaction as legitimate is having a users money stolen, which the credit card company typically reimburses. On the other hand, the penalty for mislabeling a legitimate transaction as fraud is having the user frozen out of their finances and unable to make payments. There is a very fine tradeoff between these two consequences

The Question I have?

Given that the potential costs for FP and FN differ in magnitude from business to business, it's left for the respective organisations to apply relative weights to balance the effect of FP or FN on their businesses.

For Capital one, in a fraud situation, what is the cost of 1 FN vs 1 FP? or 1FN to 5FP. It's hard to assume for me but i am quite intrigued to know the answer of this !!

Assumptions

Precision and recall numbers depend on the actual probability of fraud in the data. Where high precision relates to a low false positive rate, and high recall relates to a low false negative rate.

  • My assumption is that generally fraudulent cases are very small in number so precision might be low, but recall should be high i.e we should try to lower the FN
  • Perhaps with sampling techniques the trade-off will change a bit, we will try to increase the TP as well while trying to lower the FP

4. Evaluation Metrics¶

Choose the correct set of Perfomance evaluation metrics

Like we saw earlier as well, the data provided is highly imbalanced. So we have to keep in mind when using an evaluation metric to see how good our model is.

  • About Accuracy Score: NO

    Using accuracy score as a evaluation metrics for such highly imbalanced dataset is not a good measure of classifier performance.
    In our data the distribution of majority-to-minority class is 98.5:1.5 then labelling all data points as majority class would give us around 98% accuracy which is really good score in predictive modelling. But in our case the classifier algorithm has not learnt anything about the problem at hand.

  • Confusion Matrix

    Confusion matrix will tell us about True positives, True negatives, False positives, False negatives which would be better to evaluate in our case as it will show the inorrect predictions made as well, which will give us much deeper insight to the errors made by model.
    We can prioritize and tweak/reduce FN (Model predicted not-fraud but actually it was a fraud) and FP ( Model predicted fraud but actually it was a non-fraud) while increasing TP

  • AUC-ROC

    The Curve will tell us about how good the model can distinguish between Fradulent & Non-Fraudulent classes. If it's a fraud or not - which is what we want in our case. The more the AUC the better the model is.
    One thing to keep in mind is the choice of threshold value we choose will also depend on how the classifier is intended to be used.

  • Precision/Recall/F1 Score

    It tells us about the efficiency of the model, how much or data is biased towards one class and us understand whether our model is preforming well in imbalanced dataset for minority class.

  • PR Curve & AP

    In our case the data is located mostly in the negative label so weâ€™ll calculate and plot Precision on Y-axis and Recall on X-axis to see how our model is performing.

  • Macro/ micro/ weighted average

    Macro/micro/weighted average (usually over F-score) are irrelevant (unless you have resampling and have equal distributin of both classes in the set) because averaging over the two classes would take into account the majority class which is very easy to predict, so it would mask the useful information about the minority class.

Cost-sensitive weights

  • With default weights, classifier will assume that both kinds of label error i.e. false positive (FP) and false negative (FN) have the same cost. Or in other words, classifier assumes that wrong prediction of either of the labels has same cost.
  • Though both false positives and false negatives can have dire impact and is always debatable like i dicussed ealier . But i am assuming ,in fraud transactions not detecting a fraud transaction will cost an organization more than wrongly labelling a non-fraud transaction as fraud transaction.
In [97]:
# Third Approach
w = {0:2, 1:98}
lg3 = LogisticRegression(random_state=42, class_weight=w) 
lg3.fit(X_train_s,y_train)                                     
pred_lg3 = lg3.predict(X_test_s)
pred_proba_lg3 = lg3.predict_proba(X_test_s)[:,1]

In case be unbalanced label distribution, the best practice for weights is to use the inverse of the label distribution. In our set, label distribution is 2:98 so we can specify weights as inverse of label distribution. For majority class, will use weight of 1 and for minority class, will use weight of 100. So the penalty of wrong prediction of minority class would be 100 times more severe than wrong prediction of majority class. Moreover, with this class-weight values, we would expect our model to perform better then the default

3. Easy Ensemble¶

The Easy Ensemble involves creating balanced samples of the training dataset by selecting all examples from the minority class and a subset from the majority class.Rather than using pruned decision trees, boosted decision trees are used on each subset, specifically the AdaBoost algorithm.

AdaBoost works by first fitting a decision tree on the dataset, then determining the errors made by the tree and weighing the examples in the dataset by those errors so that more attention is paid to the misclassified examples and less to the correctly classified examples.

4. Weighted XGBoost¶

Two ways to handle imbalance here, these correspond to two different approaches to cost-sensitive learning.

  • The sample_weight parameter allows you to specify a different weight for each training example.
  • The scale_pos_weight parameter lets you provide a weight for an entire class of examples ("positive" class).

We can set the scale_pos_weight hyperparameter of the algorithm to indicate that our dataset has a certain ratio of positive and negative classes and XGBoost will take care of the rest.

scale_pos_weight is the ratio of number of negative class to the positive class. Best practices, if we want to train our XGBoost classifier on this dataset we would set the value of scale_pos_weight to be

[Counter({0: 535291, 1: 8376})] 535291/8376 = 63

Keeping the FN-FP in mind

Balanced Random Forest is doing a good job in keeping FP lower than the rest. However we are focusing on getting lower FN so I am leaning more toward XGB Classifier the ratio of FN-FP along with Higher TP is the best with XGB.

6. Avoiding Data Leaks¶

Summary of steps/ approaches i kept in mind to avoid Data Leaks

  • Standardizing

    In the interest of preventing information about the distribution of the test set leaking into our model, i fitted the scaler on my training data only, then standardise both training and test sets with that scaler. By fitting the scaler on the full dataset prior to splitting, information about the test set is used to transform the training set, which in turn is passed downstream and introduces data leakage

  • Cross Validation

    Splitting the data before apply Cross validation (startifiedkfold) will ensure there are no data leakage

  • oversampling

    Split the date into test and train sets BEFORE trying sampling techniques and sampling must be only done on the training dataset

8. Future work¶

Since i had quite limited time and computaional power at my disposal I tried what i could with that limitation however there are several ideas/approaches i would have pursued given more time and computational power. Some of them you already saw above in the Appendix section.

More Feature engineering

Generate more merchant related aggregate features, time related more granular features

Sampling techniques

Combo of various upsampling & undersampling techniques with applying the models of these subsets to see what gives just the best trade-off - Smote+ENN, pipeline of Under & oversampling

Hyperparameter tuning: GridsearchCV

I tried randomized grid search with only few variables as I was quite restricted by the computaional power i had but ideally i would want to experiment with much larger set of parameters on gridsearchCV (it's claculated all combinations unlike RandomizedCV) as I think it will enchance our performance

Ensemble & boosting

Trying various combinations of Stacking/ ensemble models and trying out other boosting models CAT/Lgbm

Learn about Autoencoders

I have not worked with autoencoders and i don't have much idea about the topic but this would be a good oppurtunity to learn about it as it helps in detecting anomalies/fraudulent patterns

Tweaking Threshold

In AUC-ROC the default threshold is 0.5 but i can experiment and tweak to see the ideal tradeoff by setting different thresholds (that would require internal business insights to capital one)

Multiple Recursive Feature Selection

Though i did use this approach here but with more time i would do a lot more iterations & choose the most important features and retrain the model using the handful selected features

Access to cloud/clusters

With access to higher computational power,I am confident that i can increase the performance by a good margin.
